        <scopecontent encodinganalog="520$a">
            <head>Scope and Content </head>
            <p>Issued to Thomas Melven, shoemaker of Cannongate, Edinburgh, Scotland. Melven was
                Received and Admitted Burgess and Freeman in the presence of the Baillies John
                Learmonth, Robert Pillens, and William Berry, as well as William Hamilton,
                Treasurer. Melven appears to have been made Burgess and Freeman not only because he
                was a shoemaker, but also on the grounds that his lawful spouse, Rachael Douglas,
                was the daughter of a shoemaker and Freeman Burgess. Melven paid five merks of Scots
                money for the honor. Freemen and Burgesses date to the 15th century. No man could
                carry on a trade or business unless he was a Burgess of the town in which he plied
                his vocation. The ticket is signed by James Leach. </p>
        </scopecontent>
